<div  lang="en"><div class="postArticle-content js-postField js-notesSource js-trackedPost" data-post-id="9cc27ec09ecb" data-source="post_page" data-collection-id="98b271672773" data-tracking-context="postPage" nodeIndex="48"><section name="91e1" class="section section--body section--first section--last" nodeIndex="51"><div class="section-content" nodeIndex="52"><div class="section-inner sectionLayout--insetColumn _RIL_KEEPER_CLASS_" nodeIndex="53"><h2 name="8ef6" id="8ef6" class="graf graf--h4 graf-after--h3 graf--subtitle _RIL_KEEPER_CLASS_" nodeIndex="55">They might be skills, but they&rsquo;re not&nbsp;soft</h2><p name="8b83" id="8b83" class="graf graf--p graf-after--h4 _RIL_KEEPER_CLASS_" nodeIndex="56"><strong class="markup--strong markup--p-strong" nodeIndex="316">Are you good at your job?</strong></p><p name="2a3b" id="2a3b" class="graf graf--p graf-after--p _RIL_KEEPER_CLASS_" nodeIndex="57">Different, easier question: Was Ty Cobb good at baseball?</p><figure name="af8a" id="af8a" class="graf graf--figure graf-after--p _RIL_KEEPER_CLASS_ _RIL_KEEPER_CLASS_" nodeIndex="59"><div class="aspectRatioPlaceholder is-locked" nodeIndex="58"><div class="aspectRatioPlaceholder-fill" nodeIndex="60"></div><div id="RIL_IMG_1" class="RIL_IMG"></div></div></figure><p name="5bf9" id="5bf9" class="graf graf--p graf-after--figure _RIL_KEEPER_CLASS_" nodeIndex="61">The apocryphal story is that Ty Cobb was a jerk. His teammates didn&rsquo;t like him very much. But he&rsquo;s still in the Hall of Fame. That&rsquo;s because baseball keeps score&hellip; of hits, of runs and of catches.</p><p name="05a2" id="05a2" class="graf graf--p graf-after--p _RIL_KEEPER_CLASS_" nodeIndex="62">What about your job? It&rsquo;s probably a bit more complex.</p><p name="47b2" id="47b2" class="graf graf--p graf-after--p _RIL_KEEPER_CLASS_" nodeIndex="63">There are linchpins, people who don&rsquo;t shirk responsibility when the chips are down. And, among others, there are connectors, people with insights, folks who never seem to lose hope. Your company is staffed with people who can&rsquo;t possibly be rated on a linear scale, because you&rsquo;re not baseball players. You are managers and inventors and leaders and promise-makers and supporters and bureaucrats and detail-oriented factotums.</p><p name="f484" id="f484" class="graf graf--p graf-after--p _RIL_KEEPER_CLASS_" nodeIndex="64">And yet&hellip;</p><p name="0f84" id="0f84" class="graf graf--p graf-after--p _RIL_KEEPER_CLASS_" nodeIndex="65">And yet we persist in hiring and training as if we&rsquo;re a baseball team, as if easily defined skills are all that matter.</p><p name="948e" id="948e" class="graf graf--p graf-after--p _RIL_KEEPER_CLASS_" nodeIndex="66">What causes successful organizations to fail? Stocks to fade, innovations to slow, customers to jump ship?</p><p name="915a" id="915a" class="graf graf--p graf-after--p _RIL_KEEPER_CLASS_" nodeIndex="67">We can agree that certain focused skills are essential. That hiring coders who can&rsquo;t code, salespeople who can&rsquo;t sell or architects who can&rsquo;t architect is a short road to failure.</p><p name="d2ed" id="d2ed" class="graf graf--p graf-after--p _RIL_KEEPER_CLASS_" nodeIndex="68">These skills&#8202;&mdash;&#8202;let&rsquo;s call them vocational skills&#8202;&mdash;&#8202;have become the backbone of the HR process.</p><p name="fbac" id="fbac" class="graf graf--p graf-after--p _RIL_KEEPER_CLASS_" nodeIndex="69">But how to explain that similar organizations with similarly vocationally-skilled people find themselves with very different outcomes?</p><p name="9fa7" id="9fa7" class="graf graf--p graf-after--p _RIL_KEEPER_CLASS_" nodeIndex="70">By misdefining &lsquo;vocational&rsquo; and focusing on the apparently essential skills, we&rsquo;ve diminished the value of the skills that actually matter. Most of the textbooks business students experience and the tests business students take are about these vocational skills, the checkboxes that have to be checked.</p><p name="26d3" id="26d3" class="graf graf--p graf-after--p _RIL_KEEPER_CLASS_" nodeIndex="71">But we give too little respect to the other skills when we call them &ldquo;soft&rdquo; and imply that they&rsquo;re optional.</p><p name="a977" id="a977" class="graf graf--p graf-after--p _RIL_KEEPER_CLASS_" nodeIndex="72">It turns out that what actually separates thriving organizations from struggling ones are the difficult-to-measure attitudes, processes and perceptions of the people who do the work.</p><p name="b618" id="b618" class="graf graf--p graf-after--p _RIL_KEEPER_CLASS_" nodeIndex="73">Culture defeats strategy, every time.</p><p name="a4fc" id="a4fc" class="graf graf--p graf-after--p _RIL_KEEPER_CLASS_" nodeIndex="74">And yet&hellip;</p><p name="9346" id="9346" class="graf graf--p graf-after--p _RIL_KEEPER_CLASS_" nodeIndex="75">Organizations spend a ton of time measuring the vocational skills, because they can. Because there&rsquo;s a hundred years of history. And mostly, because it&rsquo;s safe. It&rsquo;s not personal, it&rsquo;s business.</p><p name="6dd6" id="6dd6" class="graf graf--p graf-after--p _RIL_KEEPER_CLASS_" nodeIndex="76">We know how to measure typing speed. We have a lot more trouble measuring passion or commitment.</p><p name="01c2" id="01c2" class="graf graf--p graf-after--p _RIL_KEEPER_CLASS_" nodeIndex="77">Organizations give feedback on vocational skill output daily, and save the other stuff for the annual review if they measure it at all.</p><p name="134f" id="134f" class="graf graf--p graf-after--p _RIL_KEEPER_CLASS_" nodeIndex="78">And organizations hire and fire based on vocational skill output all the time, but practically need an act of the Board to get rid of a negative thinker, a bully or a sloth (if he&rsquo;s good at something measurable).</p><h3 name="4c26" id="4c26" class="graf graf--h3 graf-after--p _RIL_KEEPER_CLASS_" nodeIndex="79">Theft</h3><p name="c4f1" id="c4f1" class="graf graf--p graf-after--h3 _RIL_KEEPER_CLASS_" nodeIndex="80">If an employee at your organization walked out with a brand-new laptop every day, you&rsquo;d have him arrested, or at least fired. If your bookkeeper was embezzling money every month, you&rsquo;d do the same thing.</p><p name="9f86" id="9f86" class="graf graf--p graf-after--p _RIL_KEEPER_CLASS_" nodeIndex="81">But when an employee demoralizes the entire team by undermining a project, or when a team member checks out and doesn&rsquo;t pull his weight, or when a bully causes future stars to quit the organization&#8202;&mdash;&#8202;too often, we shrug and point out that this person has tenure, or vocational skills or isn&rsquo;t so bad.</p><p name="f29e" id="f29e" class="graf graf--p graf-after--p _RIL_KEEPER_CLASS_" nodeIndex="82">But they&rsquo;re stealing from us.</p><h3 name="be89" id="be89" class="graf graf--h3 graf-after--p _RIL_KEEPER_CLASS_" nodeIndex="83">What can we&nbsp;teach?</h3><p name="3468" id="3468" class="graf graf--p graf-after--h3 _RIL_KEEPER_CLASS_" nodeIndex="84">Along the way, we&rsquo;ve confirmed that vocational skills can be taught (you&rsquo;re not born knowing engineering or copywriting or even graphic design, therefore they must be something we can teach), while we let ourselves off the hook when it comes to decision making, eager participation, dancing with fear, speaking with authority, working in teams, seeing the truth, speaking the truth, inspiring others, doing more than we&rsquo;re asked, caring and being willing to change things.</p><p name="f50d" id="f50d" class="graf graf--p graf-after--p _RIL_KEEPER_CLASS_" nodeIndex="85">We underinvest in this training, fearful that these things are innate and can&rsquo;t be taught.</p><p name="9345" id="9345" class="graf graf--p graf-after--p _RIL_KEEPER_CLASS_" nodeIndex="86">We call these skills <em class="markup--em markup--p-em" nodeIndex="317">soft</em>, making it easy for us to move on to something seemingly more urgent.</p><p name="7625" id="7625" class="graf graf--p graf-after--p _RIL_KEEPER_CLASS_" nodeIndex="87">We rarely hire for these attributes because we&rsquo;ve persuaded ourselves that vocational skills are impersonal and easier to measure.</p><p name="26ec" id="26ec" class="graf graf--p graf-after--p _RIL_KEEPER_CLASS_" nodeIndex="88">And we fire slowly (and retrain rarely) when these skills are missing, because we&rsquo;re worried about stepping on toes, being called out for getting personal, or possibly, wasting time on a lost cause.</p><p name="574e" id="574e" class="graf graf--p graf-after--p _RIL_KEEPER_CLASS_" nodeIndex="89">Which is crazy, because infants aren&rsquo;t good at any of the soft skills. Of course we learn them. We learn them accidentally, by osmosis, by the collisions we have with teachers, parents, bosses and the world. But just because they&rsquo;re difficult to measure doesn&rsquo;t mean we can&rsquo;t improve them, can&rsquo;t practice them, can&rsquo;t change.</p><p name="e43c" id="e43c" class="graf graf--p graf-after--p _RIL_KEEPER_CLASS_" nodeIndex="90">Of course we can.</p><p name="a393" id="a393" class="graf graf--p graf-after--p _RIL_KEEPER_CLASS_" nodeIndex="91">Let&rsquo;s call them real skills, not soft.</p><p name="3533" id="3533" class="graf graf--p graf-after--p _RIL_KEEPER_CLASS_" nodeIndex="92">Yes, they&rsquo;re interpersonal skills. Leadership skills. The skills of charisma and diligence and contribution. But these modifiers, while accurate, somehow edge them away from the vocational skills, the skills that we actually hire for, the skills we measure a graduate degree on.</p><p name="8053" id="8053" class="graf graf--p graf-after--p _RIL_KEEPER_CLASS_" nodeIndex="93">So let&rsquo;s uncomfortably call them <em class="markup--em markup--p-em" nodeIndex="318">real skills</em> instead.</p><p name="27f2" id="27f2" class="graf graf--p graf-after--p _RIL_KEEPER_CLASS_" nodeIndex="94">Real because they work, because they&rsquo;re at the heart of what we need to today.</p><p name="e98c" id="e98c" class="graf graf--p graf-after--p _RIL_KEEPER_CLASS_" nodeIndex="95">Real because even if you&rsquo;ve got the vocational skills, you&rsquo;re no help to us without these human skills, the things that we can&rsquo;t write down, or program a computer to do.</p><p name="c030" id="c030" class="graf graf--p graf-after--p _RIL_KEEPER_CLASS_" nodeIndex="96">Real skills can&rsquo;t replace vocational skills, of course not. What they can do is amplify the things you&rsquo;ve already been measuring.</p><p name="f24f" id="f24f" class="graf graf--p graf-after--p _RIL_KEEPER_CLASS_" nodeIndex="97">Imagine a team member with all the traditional vocational skills: productive, skilled, experienced. A resume that can prove it.</p><p name="98e6" id="98e6" class="graf graf--p graf-after--p _RIL_KEEPER_CLASS_" nodeIndex="98">That&rsquo;s fine, it&rsquo;s the baseline.</p><p name="6c8a" id="6c8a" class="graf graf--p graf-after--p _RIL_KEEPER_CLASS_" nodeIndex="99">Now, add to that: Perceptive, charismatic, driven, focused, goal-setting, inspiring and motivated. A deep listener, with patience.</p><p name="f8d1" id="f8d1" class="graf graf--p graf-after--p _RIL_KEEPER_CLASS_" nodeIndex="100">What happens to your organization when someone like that joins your team?</p><h3 name="aa2d" id="aa2d" class="graf graf--h3 graf-after--p _RIL_KEEPER_CLASS_" nodeIndex="101">Work to be&nbsp;done</h3><p name="3f03" id="3f03" class="graf graf--p graf-after--h3 _RIL_KEEPER_CLASS_" nodeIndex="102">Writing in the Harvard Business Review, Lou Solomon reports that 69% of managers are uncomfortable communicating with their employees. The only surprising thing about this statistic is how low it is.</p><p name="3284" id="3284" class="graf graf--p graf-after--p _RIL_KEEPER_CLASS_" nodeIndex="103">How do we build people-centric organizations while also accepting the fact that two-thirds of our managers (presumably well-paid, well-trained and integral to our success) are uncomfortable doing the essential part of their job?</p><p name="b3ca" id="b3ca" class="graf graf--p graf-after--p _RIL_KEEPER_CLASS_" nodeIndex="104">In a recent survey, the Graduate Management Admission Council, the folks who own the GMAT exam, reported that although MBA&rsquo;s were strong in analytical aptitude, quantitative expertise, and information-gathering ability, they were sorely lacking in other critical areas that employers find equally attractive: strategic thinking, written and oral communication, leadership, and adaptability.</p><p name="c52b" id="c52b" class="graf graf--p graf-after--p _RIL_KEEPER_CLASS_" nodeIndex="105">Are these mutually exclusive? Must we trade one for the other?</p><h3 name="9228" id="9228" class="graf graf--h3 graf-after--p _RIL_KEEPER_CLASS_" nodeIndex="106"><strong class="markup--strong markup--h3-strong" nodeIndex="319">An Encyclopedia of Real&nbsp;Skills</strong></h3><p name="4fe8" id="4fe8" class="graf graf--p graf-after--h3 _RIL_KEEPER_CLASS_" nodeIndex="107">The fact that there isn&rsquo;t an accepted taxonomy of real skills demonstrates just how little effort organizations large and small have put into finding, improving and developing real skills among their teams.</p><p name="b6ba" id="b6ba" class="graf graf--p graf-after--p _RIL_KEEPER_CLASS_" nodeIndex="108">In this first draft, we&rsquo;ve chosen five large categories and then given examples of each. Not a definitive taxonomy, but a start, a way to move the conversation and the investment forward.</p><p name="589f" id="589f" class="graf graf--p graf-after--p _RIL_KEEPER_CLASS_" nodeIndex="109">The five categories might include:</p><p name="2e91" id="2e91" class="graf graf--p graf-after--p _RIL_KEEPER_CLASS_" nodeIndex="110"><strong class="markup--strong markup--p-strong" nodeIndex="320">Self Control</strong>&#8202;&mdash;&#8202;Once you&rsquo;ve decided that something is important, are you able to persist in doing it, without letting distractions or bad habits get in the way? <em class="markup--em markup--p-em" nodeIndex="321">Doing things for the long run that you might not feel like doing in the short run.</em></p><p name="437b" id="437b" class="graf graf--p graf-after--p _RIL_KEEPER_CLASS_" nodeIndex="111"><strong class="markup--strong markup--p-strong" nodeIndex="322">Productivity</strong>&#8202;&mdash;&#8202;Are you skilled with your instrument? Are you able to use your insights and your commitment to actually move things forward? <em class="markup--em markup--p-em" nodeIndex="323">Getting non-vocational tasks done.</em></p><p name="7be9" id="7be9" class="graf graf--p graf-after--p _RIL_KEEPER_CLASS_" nodeIndex="112"><strong class="markup--strong markup--p-strong" nodeIndex="324">Wisdom</strong>&#8202;&mdash;&#8202;Have you learned things that are difficult to glean from a textbook or a manual? <em class="markup--em markup--p-em" nodeIndex="325">Experience is how we become adults.</em></p><p name="4d9b" id="4d9b" class="graf graf--p graf-after--p _RIL_KEEPER_CLASS_" nodeIndex="113"><strong class="markup--strong markup--p-strong" nodeIndex="326">Perception</strong>&#8202;&mdash;&#8202;Do you have the experience and the practice to see the world clearly? <em class="markup--em markup--p-em" nodeIndex="327">Seeing things before others have to point them out.</em></p><p name="509a" id="509a" class="graf graf--p graf-after--p _RIL_KEEPER_CLASS_" nodeIndex="114"><strong class="markup--strong markup--p-strong" nodeIndex="328">Influence</strong>&#8202;&mdash;&#8202;Have you developed the skills needed to persuade others to take action? <em class="markup--em markup--p-em" nodeIndex="329">Charisma is just one form of this skill.</em></p><h3 name="4358" id="4358" class="graf graf--h3 graf-after--p _RIL_KEEPER_CLASS_" nodeIndex="115">Self Control</h3><p name="4341" id="4341" class="graf graf--p graf-after--h3 _RIL_KEEPER_CLASS_" nodeIndex="116">Adaptability to changing requirements</p><p name="3ec5" id="3ec5" class="graf graf--p graf-after--p _RIL_KEEPER_CLASS_" nodeIndex="117">Agility in the face of unexpected obstacles</p><p name="ac72" id="ac72" class="graf graf--p graf-after--p _RIL_KEEPER_CLASS_" nodeIndex="118">Alacrity and the ability to start and stop quickly</p><p name="1e7e" id="1e7e" class="graf graf--p graf-after--p _RIL_KEEPER_CLASS_" nodeIndex="119">Authenticity and consistent behavior</p><p name="585f" id="585f" class="graf graf--p graf-after--p _RIL_KEEPER_CLASS_" nodeIndex="120">Bouncing back from failure</p><p name="14f5" id="14f5" class="graf graf--p graf-after--p _RIL_KEEPER_CLASS_" nodeIndex="121">Coach-ability and the desire to coach others</p><p name="3452" id="3452" class="graf graf--p graf-after--p _RIL_KEEPER_CLASS_" nodeIndex="122">Collaborative mindset</p><p name="1d01" id="1d01" class="graf graf--p graf-after--p _RIL_KEEPER_CLASS_" nodeIndex="123">Compassion for those in need</p><p name="290b" id="290b" class="graf graf--p graf-after--p _RIL_KEEPER_CLASS_" nodeIndex="124">Competitiveness</p><p name="cb09" id="cb09" class="graf graf--p graf-after--p _RIL_KEEPER_CLASS_" nodeIndex="125">Conscientiousness in keeping promises</p><p name="b8e4" id="b8e4" class="graf graf--p graf-after--p _RIL_KEEPER_CLASS_" nodeIndex="126">Customer service passion</p><p name="379a" id="379a" class="graf graf--p graf-after--p _RIL_KEEPER_CLASS_" nodeIndex="127">Eagerness to learn from criticism</p><p name="b586" id="b586" class="graf graf--p graf-after--p _RIL_KEEPER_CLASS_" nodeIndex="128">Emotional intelligence</p><p name="998a" id="998a" class="graf graf--p graf-after--p _RIL_KEEPER_CLASS_" nodeIndex="129">Endurance for the long haul</p><p name="c3cf" id="c3cf" class="graf graf--p graf-after--p _RIL_KEEPER_CLASS_" nodeIndex="130">Enthusiasm for the work</p><p name="2c05" id="2c05" class="graf graf--p graf-after--p _RIL_KEEPER_CLASS_" nodeIndex="131">Ethics even when not under scrutiny</p><p name="f1d2" id="f1d2" class="graf graf--p graf-after--p _RIL_KEEPER_CLASS_" nodeIndex="132">Etiquette</p><p name="2bab"